                            <comment id="13214126" author="stack" created="Thu, 23 Feb 2012 00:28:37 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;So if we can add inline block index on required columns, the second column family then is not needed.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What would this look like He?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13214915" author="he yongqiang" created="Thu, 23 Feb 2012 18:30:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;@stack, we haven&apos;t thought that in much detail, but we can start the discussion by an example.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let&apos;s say there is one column family, and it only contains one type column whose name is a combine of &apos;string and ts&apos;. So the data is sorted by &apos;string&apos; first. But one query wants the data to be sorted by ts instead.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13214922" author="lhofhansl" created="Thu, 23 Feb 2012 18:41:59 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;@He. So you found the row and then you search inside the row with a ColumnRange or ColumnPrefix filter?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13215002" author="he yongqiang" created="Thu, 23 Feb 2012 20:10:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;@lars, in today&apos;s implementation we actually create another column family and reorg the column name to be &apos;ts and string&apos;, so the data is sorted by ts in this new column family. And we redirect the query to use the second column family. But this approach duplicates data. &lt;br/&gt;
Without the second column family, we can do a search once we found the row. but that requires searching all data with the target row key. It hurts cpu. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
